  </section>

  <!-- 2. SEO content -->
  <section class="seo-content">
    <div class="content-inner">
      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">Why there are four different systems</h2>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Metric is the only system that tells you what the needle actually
        measures. A 4.0 mm needle is 4.0 mm. Done.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        US sizes are labels. A US 7 means 4.5 mm and a US 8 means 5.0 mm, but
        nothing about those numbers hints at a diameter.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Old UK and Canadian sizes run backward. A UK 14 is tiny, and the numbers
        shrink as needles grow until you hit 0, 00, and 000. Most modern UK
        patterns give metric, but the old system still shows up on vintage
        needles and secondhand pattern leaflets.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Japanese sizes track close to metric but not perfectly. Japanese size 6
        is 3.9 mm, Japanese size 8 is 4.5 mm. That offset matters most in fine
        gauges where a few tenths of a millimeter change the finished fabric.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">When metric is the safe bet</h2>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Trust the millimeter size first. It's the actual measurement, and it
        sidesteps conversion mistakes entirely.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        When a pattern calls for "US 7," what you need in your hand is 4.5 mm.
        Some brands print both numbers on the needle. Some don't. Old markings
        wear off. A needle gauge tool is worth keeping nearby for exactly this
        reason.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">Common conversion pitfalls</h2>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">A few sizes trip people up consistently.</p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        <strong>The UK reversal.</strong> US sizes go up as needles get bigger. Old
        UK sizes go down. A US 6 is 4.0 mm. A UK 6 is 5.0 mm. Swap those and your
        swatch is off by a full millimeter before you've knit a single row. That trips
        up more people than you'd expect.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        <strong>The missing one-to-one matches.</strong> Not every metric size has
        a clean equivalent in every other system. A 3.0 mm needle is sometimes labeled
        US 2.5 by some brands, while other charts place it between US 2 and US 3.
        A 3.5 mm needle usually has no old UK equivalent at all. When that happens,
        go back to the mm size and ignore the rest.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        <strong>Japanese near-misses.</strong> Japanese sizes don't line up cleanly
        with US numbers. Japanese size 8 is 4.5 mm (matching US 7), but Japanese size
        5 is 3.6 mm and doesn't sit neatly in the US system at all. If you're working
        from a Japanese pattern, match the mm value. Not the printed number. Always
        the mm value.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        <strong>Half sizes and odd sizes are real.</strong> 2.5 mm, 3.0 mm, and 6.5
        mm needles are standard production sizes even if your interchangeable set
        skipped them. This is why "go up half a size" sometimes turns into a rummage
        through the whole project bag.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        <strong>Old pattern leaflets give no system label.</strong> A pattern from
        the 1970s that says "size 6 needles" could mean US 6 (4.0 mm) or UK 6 (5.0
        mm) depending on which country published it. Check the publisher, then check
        the chart.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">Needle size and yarn weight pairing</h2>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        The chart can get you into the right neighborhood. Your swatch decides
        the exact address.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        The current Craft Yarn Council weight system pairs lace with 1.5 to 2.25
        mm, Super Fine with 2.25 to 3.25 mm, Fine with 3.25 to 3.75 mm, Light
        with 3.75 to 4.5 mm, Medium with 4.5 to 5.5 mm, Bulky with 5.5 to 8 mm,
        Super Bulky with 8 to 12.75 mm, and Jumbo at 12.75 mm and up.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Those ranges overlap on purpose. DK can make a firm hat fabric on a
        smaller needle or an airy shawl fabric on a larger one. The pattern
        gauge tells you which direction the designer intended. If you're not
        sure which yarn category you're holding, the <a
          href="/tools/yarn-weight-chart/">yarn weight chart</a
        > is the better place to start.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">How to measure unmarked needles</h2>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Vintage needles, hand-turned wooden needles, and well-used
        interchangeables all end up with missing markings sooner or later. A
        needle gauge (sometimes called a needle sizer) fixes that. Slide the
        shaft into the holes until you find the one that fits cleanly without
        forcing.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Measure on the shaft, not the tip. The tapered point reads smaller than
        the working part of the needle. Wrong answer every time.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-fade-up">
        Most needle gauges show metric and US sizes, some include Japanese
        sizing too. If yours doesn't, use this needle size guide to find the mm
        equivalent and then knit a quick <a
          href="/articles/how-to-measure-knitting-gauge/">gauge swatch</a
        > to confirm before you commit to the full project. If you're also choosing
        a <a href="/articles/knitting-needle-materials/">needle material</a>,
        that's a separate decision from size.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 3. FAQ -->
  <section class="tool-faq">
    <div class="faq-inner">
      <h2 class="gs-clip-reveal">Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details class="gs-faq-item">
          <summary
            >Can I substitute a close needle size if I don't have the exact one? <span
              class="faq-icon"
              aria-hidden="true">+</span
            ></summary
          >
          <p>
            You can, but a 0.5 mm jump often shifts gauge enough to matter.
            Swatch again for anything fitted.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="gs-faq-item">
          <summary
            >Are needle sizes the same across all brands? <span
              class="faq-icon"
              aria-hidden="true">+</span
            ></summary
          >
          <p>
            They should be. In practice there are slight differences, especially
            on cheaper sets or older needles. If your gauge is persistently off,
            measure the needle.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="gs-faq-item">
          <summary
            >What about circular needle sizes? <span
              class="faq-icon"
              aria-hidden="true">+</span
            ></summary
          >
          <p>
            Same sizing as straights. The size describes tip diameter, not cable
            length. A 4.5 mm circular is a 4.5 mm needle whether the cable is
            short for a hat or long for magic loop.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="gs-faq-item">
          <summary
            >Do I need every needle size? <span
              class="faq-icon"
              aria-hidden="true">+</span
            ></summary
          >
          <p>
            No. Most knitters live in a handful of sizes matching the yarns they
            use most. If you're working with Medium and Light yarns, you'll
            reach for 3.75 to 5.5 mm constantly.
          </p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. Waitlist CTA -->
  <section class="waitlist-cta" id="join">
    <div class="waitlist-inner">
      <form class="waitlist-form" action="#" method="post" id="waitlist-form">
        <label class="visually-hidden" for="waitlist-website"
          >Leave this field empty</label
        >
        <input
          class="visually-hidden"
          id="waitlist-website"
          name="website"
          type="text"
          tabindex="-1"
          autocomplete="off"
        />
        <div class="waitlist-content-layer" id="waitlist-content-layer">
          <h2 class="waitlist-head">
            Where every stitch<br /><em>counts.</em>
          </h2>
          <div class="waitlist-row" id="waitlist-row" data-content>
            <input
              type="email"
              name="email"
              placeholder="your@email.com"
              required
              class="waitlist-input"
            />
            <button type="submit" class="waitlist-btn" id="waitlist-btn"
              >Notify me at launch</button
            >
          </div>
          <p
            class="waitlist-success"
            id="waitlist-success"
            aria-hidden="true"
            hidden
          >
            You're in! We'll notify you at launch.
          </p>
          <p class="waitlist-meta">
            Coming {PRICING.launchMonthLabel} to Google Play. Launch price <strong
              ><RegionalPrice phase="launch" /></strong
            >. Regular price <strong><RegionalPrice phase="permanent" /></strong
            > later. <RegionalPricingNote />
          </p>
          <p
            class="waitlist-error"
            id="waitlist-error"
            role="alert"
            aria-live="polite"
            hidden
          >
          </p>
        </div>
      </form>
    </div>
  </section>
</PageLayout>

<script>
  import { gsap } from "gsap";
  import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/ScrollTrigger";

  gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

  const prefersReducedMotion = window.matchMedia(
    "(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)",
  ).matches;

  // --- Search filtering (works regardless of motion preference) ---
  const searchInput = document.getElementById(
    "needle-search",
  ) as HTMLInputElement | null;
  const table = document.getElementById("needle-table");
  const noResults = document.getElementById("no-results");

  if (searchInput && table && noResults) {
    const rows = table.querySelectorAll("tbody tr");

    searchInput.addEventListener("input", () => {
      const raw = searchInput.value.trim().toLowerCase();

      if (!raw) {
        rows.forEach((r) => ((r as HTMLElement).style.display = ""));
        noResults.hidden = true;
        return;
      }

      // Detect system prefix
      let targetCol: string | null = null;
      let query = raw;

      if (raw.startsWith("us ")) {
        targetCol = "us";
        query = raw.slice(3).trim();
      } else if (raw.startsWith("uk ")) {
        targetCol = "uk";
        query = raw.slice(3).trim();
      } else if (raw.startsWith("jp ") || raw.startsWith("japanese ")) {
        targetCol = "jp";
        query = raw.replace(/^(jp|japanese)\s+/, "").trim();
      }

      let visibleCount = 0;

      rows.forEach((r) => {
        const row = r as HTMLElement;
        const mm = row.dataset.mm || "";
        const us = row.dataset.us || "";
        const uk = row.dataset.uk || "";
        const jp = row.dataset.jp || "";

        const match =
          targetCol === "us"
            ? us === query
            : targetCol === "uk"
              ? uk === query
              : targetCol === "jp"
                ? jp === query
                : mm.startsWith(query) ||
                  us === query ||
                  uk === query ||
                  jp === query;

        row.style.display = match ? "" : "none";
        if (match) visibleCount++;
      });

      noResults.hidden = visibleCount > 0;
    });
  }

  if (!prefersReducedMotion) {
    // --- Hero entrance timeline ---
    const heroTl = gsap.timeline({ defaults: { ease: "power3.out" } });

    heroTl.from(
      ".gs-hero",
      {
        opacity: 0,
        y: 12,
        duration: 0.5,
        stagger: 0.15,
      },
      0.2,
    );

    // H1 letter stagger — wrap each word so browsers can't break mid-word
    const h1El = document.querySelector(".h1-chars");
    if (h1El) {
      const text = h1El.textContent || "";
      h1El.textContent = "";
      const chars: HTMLSpanElement[] = [];
      const words = text.split(" ");
      words.forEach((word, wi) => {
        const wordSpan = document.createElement("span");
        wordSpan.className = "h1-word";
        for (const c of word) {
          const span = document.createElement("span");
          span.className = "h1-char";
          span.textContent = c;
          wordSpan.appendChild(span);
          chars.push(span);
        }
        h1El.appendChild(wordSpan);
        if (wi < words.length - 1) {
          h1El.appendChild(document.createTextNode(" "));
        }
      });

      heroTl.from(
        chars,
        {
          opacity: 0,
          x: -20,
          duration: 0.4,
          stagger: 0.03,
          ease: "power2.out",
        },
        0.1,
      );
    }

    // Table + search fade in
    heroTl.from(
      ".gs-form",
      {
        opacity: 0,
        y: 16,
        duration: 0.5,
      },
      0.6,
    );

    // --- Scroll-triggered: clip-reveal H2s ---
    document.querySelectorAll(".gs-clip-reveal").forEach((el) => {
      gsap.set(el, { clipPath: "inset(0 100% 0 0)" });
      gsap.to(el, {
        clipPath: "inset(0 0% 0 0)",
        duration: 0.8,
        ease: "power3.inOut",
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: el,
          start: "top 85%",
          once: true,
        },
      });
    });

    // --- Scroll-triggered: fade up paragraphs ---
    document.querySelectorAll(".gs-fade-up").forEach((el) => {
      gsap.from(el, {
        opacity: 0,
        y: 24,
        duration: 0.6,
        ease: "power2.out",
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: el,
          start: "top 88%",
          once: true,
        },
      });
    });

    // --- FAQ items staggered on scroll ---
    const faqItems = document.querySelectorAll(".gs-faq-item");
    if (faqItems.length) {
      gsap.from(faqItems, {
        opacity: 0,
        y: 16,
        duration: 0.4,
        stagger: 0.08,
        ease: "power2.out",
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: faqItems[0],
          start: "top 85%",
          once: true,
        },
      });
    }

    // --- FAQ accordion smooth height ---
    document.querySelectorAll(".gs-faq-item").forEach((details) => {
      const summary = details.querySelector("summary");
      const content = details.querySelector("p");
      if (!summary || !content) return;

      summary.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        if (details.hasAttribute("open")) {
          gsap.to(content, {
            height: 0,
            opacity: 0,
            duration: 0.3,
            ease: "power2.inOut",
            onComplete: () => {
              details.removeAttribute("open");
              gsap.set(content, { height: "auto", opacity: 1 });
            },
          });
        } else {
          details.setAttribute("open", "");
          const h = content.scrollHeight;
          gsap.set(content, { height: 0, opacity: 0 });
          gsap.to(content, {
            height: h,
            opacity: 1,
            duration: 0.3,
            ease: "power2.out",
          });
        }
      });
    });
  }

  // --- Waitlist form states ---
  const waitlistForm = document.getElementById(
    "waitlist-form",
  ) as HTMLFormElement | null;
  const waitlistContent = document.getElementById("waitlist-row");
  const waitlistSuccess = document.getElementById("waitlist-success");
  const waitlistButton = document.getElementById("waitlist-btn");
  const waitlistError = document.getElementById("waitlist-error");
  const originalWaitlistButtonText = waitlistButton
    ? waitlistButton.textContent
    : "Notify me at launch";

  const showWaitlistSuccess = () => {
    if (waitlistContent) waitlistContent.style.display = "none";
    if (waitlistError) {
      waitlistError.hidden = true;
      waitlistError.textContent = "";
    }
    if (waitlistSuccess) {
      waitlistSuccess.hidden = false;
      waitlistSuccess.style.display = "block";
      waitlistSuccess.setAttribute("aria-hidden", "false");
    }
  };

  const showWaitlistError = (message: string) => {
    if (waitlistButton) {
      waitlistButton.removeAttribute("disabled");
      waitlistButton.textContent = originalWaitlistButtonText;
    }
    if (waitlistError) {
      waitlistError.textContent = message;
      waitlistError.hidden = false;
    }
  };

  if (waitlistForm) {
    waitlistForm.addEventListener("submit", async (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      if (!waitlistForm.reportValidity()) return;

      if (waitlistButton) {
        waitlistButton.setAttribute("disabled", "");
        waitlistButton.textContent = "Sending...";
      }
      if (waitlistError) {
        waitlistError.hidden = true;
        waitlistError.textContent = "";
      }

      const emailInput = waitlistForm.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>(
        'input[type="email"]',
      );
      const honeypot = waitlistForm.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>(
        'input[name="website"]',
      );

      try {
        const res = await fetch("https://api.finnvek.com/subscribe", {
          method: "POST",
          headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
          body: JSON.stringify({
            email: emailInput ? emailInput.value.trim() : "",
            source: "knittools",
            website: honeypot ? honeypot.value : "",
          }),
        });
        const data = await res.json().catch(() => ({}));
        if (res.ok && data.success) {
          showWaitlistSuccess();
        } else {
          showWaitlistError(
            data.error || "Something went wrong. Please try again.",
          );
        }
      } catch {
        showWaitlistError("Network error. Please check your connection.");
      }
    });
  }
</script>

